dataIdInfo.idPurp:
This [POINT] dataset represents the center location for lichen surveys done at John Muir National Historic Site. Forest Inventory and Analysis Lichen Indicator plot installation at John Muir National Historic Site On August 7th, 2014 two long-term lichen monitoring plots were installed on Mt Wanda, JOMU. Baseline lichen data was collected by lichenologist Shelly Benson, assisted by JOMU natural resource staff Desmond Murray, and Matthew Waterworth. Collection methods follow those outlined by the Forest Inventory and Analysis (FIA) Lichen Communities Indicator Program (Phase 3 Field Guide—Lichen Communities, Version 5.1, October 2011). Shelly collected and assigned abundance codes to reference specimens of each macrolichen species (foliose and fruticose lichens) observed on woody plants above 0.5 meters. Desmond and Matthew assisted by monumenting the plot, recording lichen data, and filling in the FIA plot data card and FIA Lichen Indicator off-frame stand data sheet.
Plot locations were subjectively selected based on vegetation community and aspect. Through initial scoping, we identified two tree-dominated communities likely to support lichens: coast live oak/mixed oak woodland and blue oak woodland. Several potential plot locations, in each vegetation type, were generated in GIS using the park’s vegetation map. Points were positioned so that the 34.7 meter radius plot would fit entirely within the desired vegetation community. Additionally, an effort was made to ensure that the two plots selected had different exposure (e.g. north and south).
The purpose of installing the FIA Lichen Indicator plots in different vegetation communities and on different aspects was to maximize our chance of recording as many macrolichen species as possible within the park. This study will serve as an initial lichen inventory of JOMU. The plots were permanently monumented, at plot center, with rebar and an aluminum cap stamped with the plot name: ‘lich 1’ (mixed oak woodland) and ‘lich 2’ (blue oak woodland). Additionally, the points were mapped using a Trimble Juno 3B GPS unit (note: plots will be re-mapped with a more accurate unit in the future).
References:
FIA Lichen Indicator protocols: http://www.fia.fs.fed.us/library/field-guides-methods-
proc/docs/2012/field_guide_p3_5-1_sec21_10_2011.pdf
